{
  "text": "Our goal is to fully automatically capture a personalized, rigged surface model, as used in animation, together with its sequence of skeletal poses from sparse multi-view video of general scenes where background segmentation is hard. Many multi-view markerless motion capture approaches consider model initialization and tracking separate problems [CITATION_1] . Even in recent methods working outdoors, shape and skeleton dimensions of the tracked model are either initialized manually prior to tracking [CITATION_2] , or estimated from manually segmented initialization poses [CITATION_3] . In controlled studios, static shape [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] or dimensions and pose of simple parametric human models [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] can be optimized by matching against chroma-keyed multi-view image silhouettes. Many multi-view performance capture methods [CITATION_11] deform a static full-body shape template obtained with a full-body scanner [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] , or through fitting against the visual hull [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] to match scene motion. Again, all these require controlled in-studio footage, an off-line scan, or both. Shape estimation of a parametric model in single images using shading and edge cues [CITATION_20] , actor silhouettes [CITATION_21] [CITATION_22] [CITATION_23] [CITATION_24] [CITATION_25] , or monocular pose and shape estimation from video is also feasible [CITATION_26] [CITATION_27] [CITATION_28] , but require substantial manual intervention (joint labeling, feature/pose correction, background subtraction etc.). For multi-view in-studio setups (3-4 views) , where background subtraction works, B\u0203lan et al. [CITATION_29] estimate shape and pose of the SCAPE parametric body model and Cheung et al. propose a model-free approach [CITATION_30] . Optimization is independent for each frame and requires initialization by a coarse cylindrical shape model. Implicit surface representations yield beneficial properties for pose [CITATION_31] and surface [CITATION_32] reconstruction, but do not avoid the dependency on explicit silhouette input. In contrast to all previously mentioned methods, our approach requires no manual interaction, succeeds even with only two camera views, and on scenes recorded outdoors without any background segmentation.",
  "correct_citation": {
